You need to find a vector $\mathbf{b}$ that is collinear with $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{c}$ and bisects the angle between them. From the law of cosines, the cosine of the angle bisector $\mathbf{b}$ is the average of the cosines of the angles between $\mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{b}$, and between $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}$. This implies:

\begin{align*}
| \mathbf{b} |^2
&= \frac{\|\mathbf{c}\|^2 + \|\mathbf{a}\|^2}{2}
\\\\
&= \frac{6^2 + 9^2}{2}
\\\\
&= 81
\end{align*}

Furthermore, $\mathbf{b}$ bisects the angle between $\mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{a}$ (has a dot product of $\|\mathbf{c}\| \|\mathbf{a}\| /2$), so

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c}+\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a}
&= \frac{\|\mathbf{c}\| \|\mathbf{a}\|}2,
\\\\
\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c}+\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{a}
&= 12,
\end{align*}

so \begin{align*}
\langle\mathbf{b}, (1,1,1)\rangle \cdot \langle-2, -1, 2\rangle
&= 12,
\\\\
\langle\mathbf{b}, (1,1,1)\rangle
&= -4,
\\\\
\left\langle\mathbf{b}, \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}(-2,-1,2) \right\rangle
&= -4,
\\\\
\mathbf{b}
&= -\frac{4}{\sqrt{6}} (-2, -1, 2) = \frac{2}{\sqrt{6}}(4, 2, -4).
\end{align*}[/think] <answer> $\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}}(4,2,-4)$ </answer>

problem:
